China  set its daily  reference rate 
for the yuan at the highest level since July 2005 after the  U.S.
dollar  declined yesterday on optimism  Europe  is taking steps to
address its debt crisis.  The central bank set the rate 0.21 percent stronger at
6.3623 per dollar, the biggest gain since Aug. 11. The yuan is
allowed to rise or fall no more than 0.5 percent from that level
each day.  To contact the reporter on this story:
